The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring December 3, 2009, as the International Day of Persons with Disabilities. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of renewing the global commitment to human rights and fundamental freedoms for people with disabilities. It highlights the United States' signing of the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, which advocates for equal protection and benefits for all citizens. The proclamation acknowledges the skills, achievements, and contributions of individuals with disabilities in America and worldwide. It also acknowledges the barriers and discrimination that people with disabilities still face, both in the United States and in developing nations. The proclamation calls for the integration and empowerment of individuals with disabilities, emphasizing the principles of dignity and equality. It encourages the observance of the International Day of Persons with Disabilities through appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs.